{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e429d4c8-38dc-465f-8b96-41794bbe0a9c","content":"**Best tool: `dotnet-trace`** (lightweight, .NET-specific) or **PerfView** (deeper OS-level analysis).\n\n### Quick option — `dotnet-trace`\n\n```powershell\n# Install globally\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or convert to **Speedscope** format (`--format speedscope`).\n\n### Deeper analysis — PerfView\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500\n```\n\nPerfView captures OS-level ETW events (kernel + CLR) and gives you flame graphs, call trees, and thread-time analysis — ideal for pinpointing hot paths when `dotnet-trace` isn't enough.\n\n**Recommendation:** Start with `dotnet-trace` for simplicity. Escalate to PerfView if you need kernel-level context (syscalls, I/O, contention).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"09b169ce-b407-4d99-9c02-ae9ed7b48b2a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a general knowledge question about performance diagnostics — no code changes or repository exploration needed. I'll give a concise answer.","outputTokens":360,"requestId":"CB15:3C1523:1D7F25F:209FB13:6A05252C"},"id":"779fc9d2-901a-458f-9ace-bb939a294689","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:28:22.542Z","parentId":"927aa36f-7306-4f96-88be-ef7add4f00dc"}
